# sentence_id = 521
# document_id = 0086-034
# subdoc = 25.21
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = Other things [are resolved] according to linguistic custom. They call mixed wine "wine," which is why it is written: "a greave of newly-wrought tin"; and they call those who work in iron "braziers," which is why Ganymede is said to pour wine for Zeus, although they do not drink wine. This could also be [explained] as a metaphor.
# literal_translation = The but according to the custom of-the diction. The having-been-mixed wine they-say to-be, whence has-been-made "greave of-newly-wrought tin"; and braziers the the iron working, whence is-said the Ganymede to-Zeus to-pour-wine, not drinking wine. Would-be but this-one [at least] also according to metaphor.
